-- India's poll panel nod for bank licences extends shares' record run
-- By Abhishek Vishnoi
-- Wed Apr 02, 2014 06:11AM EDT
-- None



MUMBAI, April 2 (Reuters) - Indian shares rose to record high for an eighth consecutive session after non-bank financial companies such as IDFC Ltd <IDFC.NS> surged after the election commission allowed the central bank to announce new bank licences ahead of the general elections. [ID:nI8N0L301C]

India's BSE index <.BSESN> rose as much as 0.65 percent to an all-time high of 22,592.10, while the NSE index <.NSEI> gained as much as 0.63 percent to a record high of 6,763.50. IDFC provisionally rose 4 percent while LIC Housing Finance Ltd <LICH.NS> gained 5.5 percent.